conversations.value:
To prove that Q is a logical consequence of the given set of clauses {¬P ∨ Q, P ∨ ¬R, R ∨ Q}, we use the resolution method. Resolution is a rule of inference leading to a derivation of a conclusion from premises. The goal is to show that adding the negation of Q (¬Q) to the set leads to a contradiction, thereby proving that Q must be true if all other clauses are true.

Step-by-step resolution process:

1. Extend the set of clauses by adding the negation of Q, which is the proposition we want to prove:

   Initial Set: {¬P ∨ Q, P ∨ ¬R, R ∨ Q}
   Extended Set: {¬P ∨ Q, P ∨ ¬R, R ∨ Q, ¬Q}

2. Apply the resolution rule on clauses where Q and ¬Q appear:

   a. Resolve ¬P ∨ Q and ¬Q:
      - Q and ¬Q resolve to eliminate Q, yielding ¬P.
      - New clause: {¬P}
      - Updated Set: {¬P ∨ Q, P ∨ ¬R, R ∨ Q, ¬Q, ¬P}

   b. Resolve R ∨ Q and ¬Q:
      - Q and ¬Q resolve to eliminate Q, yielding R.
      - New clause: {R}
      - Updated Set: {¬P ∨ Q, P ∨ ¬R, R ∨ Q, ¬Q, ¬P, R}

3. Further resolutions using the newly derived units ¬P and R:

   a. Resolve ¬P and P ∨ ¬R:
      - P and ¬P resolve to eliminate P, yielding ¬R.
      - New clause: {¬R}
      - Updated Set: {¬P ∨ Q, P ∨ ¬R, R ∨ Q, ¬Q, ¬P, R, ¬R}

   b. Resolve R and ¬R:
      - R and ¬R resolve to eliminate R, yielding an empty clause (denoted as {} or ⊥ meaning contradiction).
      - New clause: {}
      - Updated Set: {¬P ∨ Q, P ∨ ¬R, R ∨ Q, ¬Q, ¬P, R, ¬R, {}}

4. Conclusion:
   - We have derived an empty clause, which indicates a contradiction. This contradiction arises under the assumption that ¬Q is true. Therefore, the negation of our assumption (¬¬Q, which is Q) must be true.

   Therefore, we have proved by resolution that Q is a logical consequence of the set {¬P ∨ Q, P ∨ ¬R, R ∨ Q}.
